   <titles>
      <title>New Continuous Functions from Old</title>
      <plain.title>New Continuous from Old</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here we present a number of operations which produce new continuous functions from continuous given ones. Specifically:</para.body>
            </para>
            <ul>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The sum of two continuous function <math>
                           <latex>f,g\from D\to \RNr</latex>
                        </math> is continuous.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The product of two continuous function <math>
                           <latex>f,g\from D\to \RNr</latex>
                        </math> is continuous.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The composite of two continuous functions is continuous.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ul>
            <para>
               <para.body>Combining these results with the fact that the identity function on <math>
                     <latex>\RNr</latex>
                  </math> is continuous, we see that</para.body>
            </para>
            <ul>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Polynomial functions are continuous, and</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>rational functions are continuous away from the <math>
                           <latex>0</latex>
                        </math>’s of the denominator.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ul>
            <para>
               <para.body>We close this section with the ‘pasting lemma’. It says that two continuous functions</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>f\from \OCIntrvl{a}{b}\to \RNr</latex>
                  </math>   and   <math>
                     <latex>g\from \COIntrvl{b}{c}\to \RNr</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>may be ‘pasted’ together so as to obtain a continuous <math>
                     <latex>\OOIntrvl{a}{c}\to \RNr</latex>
                  </math> whenever <math>
                     <latex>f(b)=g(b)</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
